The 2nd Zhejiang Renju open Tournament was held in the middle of August in Haining, Zhejiang from August 14-17.

Over 60 players attended the tournament, including many of renjuclass member, such as, bawangwan, celie, intotherenju, whte, sunrain, smallpig, wolfzhou, shaoping, , etc., and also some famouse ORC players such as chinarenju

The tournament was played in 9 rounds under swiss system. The games were played according to RIF rules. Time limit for each game: 90/10/10, additional rule: each player should make 25 moves in the first 90 minutes.
After 9 rounds, Wu Hao, a 6 Dan player from Beijing won the championship with 8 points
and Wu Hao won the Beijing tournament again

2nd-6th places are:
2nd  Zhu Jianfeng  4Dan Shanghai 7points
3rd  Wu Di 5Dan Liaoning 7points
4th  Mei Fan 2Dan Jiangsu 6.5points
5th  Zhu Xiangru Zhejiang 6.5points
6th  Zhuo Miaojun Zhejiang 6points

This game was played between two strong players: Wu Di 5 Dan and Wu Hao 6 Dan in 6th round.
Maybe it is one of the most important game in the tournament. The winner of the game will have the biggest chance to win the champion of the tournament.
Wu Di is cautious to choose the D3 opening.
The 9th move must be the preparation of black, avoiding the annoying long variants of this 5th move.
this 9th move is not best in theory
but useful in short time games
but it depends on the condition that your opponent is not familiar with it
and the coming moves show that both players are quite familiar with the variant
so 9 was not a good choice
The variant after this 9th move is a little for white's favor, but hard to find comfortable solution in short time.
12-h12 also possible, but it gives black much more choices, so it is better that 12-i12.
Natural moves till 18. Both players must know the theory well.
The 19th move is pivotal in the situation.
Since white has such a promising position in the upper-left side, black has to choose some defensive move.
19-g11 is a good choice, it is also possible to choose 19-h11 or 19-f10.
Wu Di must know such moves, but maybe he wants to try some more active move than previous ones.

This game was played in the last round of the tournament between Zhu Jianfeng 4 Dan and Fan Xingchen (celie).
If Zhu Jianfeng can win the game, he still had the chance to challenge for champion title.
But it is strange that he used the 13th move in D11 opening.
The 13th move can be seen as a signal: " Oh, I want a draw, Let's play smoothly!"
In email games, many games with the similar position end with a draw.
But on the other hand, I think in short time games, the variants after this 31st move are too complicated to find comfortable position for both sides.
So anyway, it is not as easy as one expected to find draw position in real games.
so, Black decide to take the chnace?
Because in many cases, the position can become very sharp if any tinny mistake happened.
where is the 35th move? in theory?
The 35th move is not good enough. Black used fours to try to fill up the board, but it gives black too few choices.
Maybe black doesn't need too much choices at all. just one for draw is ok:)
and the next move showed that black do just want a draw
The 51st move is a obvious signal for a draw.

And finally, Zhu Jianfeng got 7 points and won the 2nd place while his biggest opponent: WuHao 6 Dan won the last round and got Champion title with 1 point advantage.
